A series of shootings in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]] began shortly before 10:00 [[UTC-4|EDT]] on October 22, 2014, when one gunman shot a [[Canadian Forces]] soldier outside the [[National War Memorial (Canada)|Canadian National War Memorial]]. The gunman then proceeded into the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament buildings]], where he was reportedly shot dead by [[Kevin Vickers]], the [[List of Sergeants-at-Arms of the Canadian House of Commons|Sergeant-at-Arms of the Canadian House of Commons]].<ref name="CBC live">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/parliament-hill-attacked-soldier-shot-at-national-war-memorial-in-ottawa-1.2808710 Parliament Hill attacked, soldier shot at National War Memorial in Ottawa]</ref><ref name="G&M breaking">[http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/breaking-news-oct-22/article21217602/ Attack on Ottawa: Police in pursuit of multiple shooters]</ref>

Subsequent to these initial events, Ottawa's downtown core was put under [[lockdown]], including Canada's Parliament and the [[University of Ottawa]].<ref name="CBC live" /><ref name="G&M breaking" /> The [[Ottawa Police Service]] stated they are investigating three shootings: one at the Canadian National War Memorial, one at [[Parliament Hill]], and one near the [[Rideau Centre]].<ref name="G&M breaking" /> The attack came a day after two Canadian Forces soldiers were struck by an [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] sympathizer in a car, killing one of them, and after Canada raised its terror threat level from low to medium.<ref name="BBC News">[http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-29724907?ns_mchannel=social&ns_campaign=bbc_breaking&ns_source=twitter&ns_linkname=news_central Shots fired inside Canada parliament]</ref>

